#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:2
msgid "Configuring Routes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:4
msgid ""
"This guide explains how to define routes in Nexus Gateway for real-world "
"service deployments. It covers path matching, authentication, rate "
"limiting, and header manipulation in a single configuration workflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:9
msgid "A Route for a Real Service"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:11
msgid ""
"The following example shows a complete route definition for a production "
"API endpoint. It combines path matching, JWT authentication, and rate "
"limiting in a single route block:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:34
msgid "Walk through each field:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:36
msgid ""
"``name`` — a unique identifier for the route, used in logs and the Admin "
"API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:38
msgid "``path`` — the path prefix to match against incoming requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:39
msgid ""
"``methods`` — restricts the route to the listed HTTP methods. Requests "
"using other methods receive a ``405 Method Not Allowed`` response."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:41
msgid "``upstream`` — the backend service address."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:42
msgid ""
"``auth`` — the authentication configuration. Here we use JWT with a JWKS "
"endpoint."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:44
msgid ""
"``rate_limit`` — applies a sliding window limit of 200 requests per "
"minute, counted per unique ``sub`` claim in the JWT."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:48
msgid "Manipulating Request Headers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:50
msgid ""
"Nexus Gateway can add, remove, or rewrite headers before forwarding a "
"request to the upstream service. This is useful for passing "
"authentication context, adding tracing headers, or removing headers that "
"should not reach backend services."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:70
msgid ""
"The ``set`` block adds or overwrites headers. The ``remove`` block "
"deletes headers from the forwarded request entirely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:74
msgid "Handling Multiple Upstreams for the Same Path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:76
msgid ""
"Some deployments require traffic splitting — for example, routing a "
"percentage of traffic to a canary deployment while the rest goes to the "
"stable version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:80
msgid "Nexus Gateway supports weighted upstream groups for this pattern:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:94
#, python-format
msgid ""
"In this configuration, 90% of traffic goes to the stable deployment and "
"10% to the canary. Adjust the weights to gradually shift traffic as "
"confidence in the canary grows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:99
msgid ""
"Weights are relative, not percentages. A configuration with weights of "
"``9`` and ``1`` produces the same distribution as ``90`` and ``10``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:103
msgid "Testing Routes Without Restarting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:105
msgid ""
"After making changes to ``nexus.yaml``, you can reload the configuration "
"without restarting the gateway process by sending a reload signal to the "
"Admin API:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:113
msgid ""
"The gateway validates the new configuration before applying it. If "
"validation fails — for example, due to a missing required field or an "
"invalid upstream address — the gateway logs the error and continues "
"running with the previous configuration. No traffic is disrupted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/guides/configuring-routes.rst:118
msgid ""
"This makes it safe to iterate on your configuration in production "
"environments."
msgstr ""

